library(ggplot2)
load("lattice.rdata")
head(food.web,3)
##   mean.length dimension
## 1        3.13     Mixed
## 2        2.71     Mixed
## 3        2.30       Two

###Question 1

ggplot(food.web, aes(x = mean.length)) +
    geom_density() +  geom_rug() +
    facet_wrap(~ dimension) + ggtitle("Q-normal plot of mean.length, faceted out by dimension for food.web dataset")

According to the graph, I don’t think the data well described by a normal distribution.

###Question 2

ggplot(food.web, aes(x = log10(mean.length))) +
    geom_density() +  geom_rug() +
    facet_wrap(~ dimension) + ggtitle("Q-normal plot of log of mean.length, faceted out by dimension for food.web dataset")

ggplot(food.web, aes(x = mean.length**(-1))) +
    geom_density() +  geom_rug() +
    facet_wrap(~ dimension) + ggtitle("Q-normal plot of reverse of mean.length, faceted out by dimension for food.web dataset")

The reverse transformation did make the graphs closer to the normal distribution.

###Question 3

#linearMod <- lm(mean.length**(-1) ~ dimension, data = food.web)

ggplot(food.web, aes(x = dimension, y = mean.length**(-1))) +
    geom_point() +
    stat_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)  + ggtitle("Q-normal plot of linear model of reverse of mean.length for food.web dataset")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

As the dimension increase, the reverse of mean.length decrease.
